member.name: T:pwiz.CLI.msdata.ChromatogramList
member.summary:
Interface for accessing chromatograms, which may be stored in memory or backed by a data file (RAW, mzXML, mzML).
- Implementations are expected to keep a chromatogram index in the form of List<ChromatogramIdentity> or equivalent. The default find*() functions search the index linearly. Implementations may provide constant time indexing.
- The semantics of chromatogram() may vary slightly with implementation. In particular, a ChromatogramList implementation that is backed by a file may choose either to cache or discard the Chromatogram for future access, with the caveat that the client may write to the underlying data.
- It is the implementation's responsibility to return a valid Chromatogram from chromatogram(). If this cannot be done, an exception must be thrown.
- The 'getBinaryData' flag is a hint if false: implementations may provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on chromatogram(index, false); implementations *must* provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on chromatogram(index, true).

member.name: T:pwiz.CLI.msdata.SpectrumList
member.summary:
Interface for accessing spectra, which may be stored in memory or backed by a data file (RAW, mzXML, mzML).
- Implementations are expected to keep a spectrum index in the form of List<SpectrumIdentity> or equivalent. The default find*() functions search the index linearly. Implementations may provide constant time indexing.
- The semantics of spectrum() may vary slightly with implementation. In particular, a SpectrumList implementation that is backed by a file may choose either to cache or discard the SpectrumPtrs for future access, with the caveat that the client may write to the underlying data.
- It is the implementation's responsibility to return a valid Spectrum^ from spectrum(). If this cannot be done, an exception must be thrown.
- The 'getBinaryData' flag is a hint if false: implementations may provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on spectrum(index, false); implementations *must* provide valid BinaryDataArrayPtrs on spectrum(index, true).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_centiRay
member.summary: centiRay: A unit of genetic map distance defined corresponding to an interval in which there is a 1% probability of X-irradiation induced breakage. To be completely specified, the unit must be qualified by the radiation in dosage in rads (e.g. cR8000), because this determines the actual breakage probability.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_centiMorgan
member.summary: centiMorgan: A unit used to express distances on a genetic map. In genetic mapping, distances between markers are determined by measuring the rate of meoitic recombination between them, which increases proportionately with the distance separating them. A cM is defined as the length of an interval in which there is a 1% probability of recombination. On the average, 1 cM is roughly equivalent to 1 megabase (Mb) of DNA, although this can vary widely due to hot and cold spots of recombination.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_milliliter_per_kilogram
member.summary: milliliter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to a thousandth of a liter per kilogram or 10^[-3] l/kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_liter_per_kilogram
member.summary: liter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to one liter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_pH
member.summary: pH: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the acidity of a solution in terms of activity of hydrogen ions (H+).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_degree_Fahrenheit
member.summary: degree Fahrenheit: A temperature unit which is equal to 5/9ths of a kelvin. Negative 40 degrees Fahrenheit is equal to negative 40 degrees Celsius.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_confluence_percentage
member.summary: confluence percentage: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the density of an attached or monolayer culture (e.g., cell culture).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_purity_percentage
member.summary: purity percentage: A dimensionless percent unit which denotes the homogeneity of a biomaterial.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_molecule_count
member.summary: molecule count: A dimensionless count unit which denotes the number of molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_fraction
member.summary: fraction: A dimensionless ratio unit which relates the part (the numerator) to the whole (the denominator).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_ratio_400000190
member.summary: ratio: A dimensionless unit which denotes an amount or magnitude of one quantity relative to another.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_count_unit
member.summary: count unit: A dimensionless unit which denotes a simple count of things.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_pi
member.summary: pi: A dimensionless unit which denoted an irrational real number, approximately equal to 3.14159 which is the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter in Euclidean geometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_percent
member.summary: percent: A dimensionless ratio unit which denotes numbers as fractions of 100.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_dimensionless_unit
member.summary: dimensionless unit: A unit which is a standard measure of physical quantity consisting of only a numerical number without any units.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_degree
member.summary: degree: A plane angle unit which is equal to 1/360 of a full rotation or 1.7453310^[-2] rad.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_meter
member.summary: kilogram per meter: An area density unit which is equal to the mass of an object in kilograms divided by one meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_linear_density_unit
member.summary: linear density unit: A density unit which is a standard measure of the mass exerting an influence on a one-dimensional object.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_density_unit
member.summary: density unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the influence exerted by some mass.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_enzyme_unit
member.summary: enzyme unit: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the amount of the enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of 1 micro mole of substrate per minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_mass_per_unit_volume
member.summary: mass per unit volume: A concentration unit which is a standard measure of the mass of a substance in a given volume (density).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_unit_per_liter
member.summary: unit per liter: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one liter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_unit_per_milliliter
member.summary: unit per milliliter: A unit per milliliter unit which is equal to one unit of an agreed arbitrary amount per one milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_unit_per_volume_unit
member.summary: unit per volume unit: A concentration unit which is a standard measure of the number of units, as an agreed arbitrary amount, of a given substance per a specific volume of solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_milligram_per_milliliter
member.summary: milligram per milliliter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in milligrams divided by the volume in milliliters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_gram_per_liter
member.summary: gram per liter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in liters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_liter
member.summary: kilogram per liter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in kilograms divided by the volume in liters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_gram_per_milliliter
member.summary: gram per milliliter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in milliliter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_quadrillion
member.summary: parts per quadrillion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[15].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_trillion
member.summary: parts per trillion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[12].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_billion
member.summary: parts per billion: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000,000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[9].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_million
member.summary: parts per million: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1,000,000 regardless of the units of measure used as long as they are the same or 1 part in 10^[6].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_thousand
member.summary: parts per thousand: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 1000 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_hundred
member.summary: parts per hundred: A dimensionless concentration notation which denotes the amount of a given substance in a total amount of 100 regardless of the units of measure as long as they are the same.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_parts_per_notation_unit
member.summary: parts per notation unit: A dimensionless concentration notation which describes the amount of one substance in another. It is the ratio of the amount of the substance of interest to the amount of that substance plus the amount of the substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_volume_percentage
member.summary: volume percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the volume of the solute in mL per 100 mL of the resulting solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_mass_volume_percentage
member.summary: mass volume percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of the substance in a mixture as a percentage of the volume of the entire mixture.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_mass_percentage
member.summary: mass percentage: A dimensionless concentration unit which denotes the mass of a substance in a mixture as a percentage of the mass of the entire mixture.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_watt_per_steradian
member.summary: watt per steradian: A radiant intensity unit which is equal to one kilogram meter squared per second cubed per steradian.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radiance_unit
member.summary: radiance unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation through space or through a material medium in the form of electromagnetic waves.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_microeinstein_per_square_meter_per_second
member.summary: microeinstein per square meter per second: An irradiance unit which is equal to one microeinstein per square meter per second or 10^[-6] microeinstein/sm^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radiant_intensity_unit
member.summary: radiant intensity unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of electromagnetic radiation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_watt_per_steradian_per_square_meter
member.summary: watt per steradian per square meter: A radiance unit which is equal to one watt of radiant power incident per steradian solid angle per one square meter projected area of the source, as viewed from the given direction.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_light_unit
member.summary: light unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the intensity of light.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_einstein_per_square_meter_per_second
member.summary: einstein per square meter per second: An irradiance unit which is equal to one einstein per square meter per second. One einstein is one mole of photons, regardless of their frequency. Therefore, the number of photons in an einstein is Avogadro's number.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_watt_per_square_meter
member.summary: watt per square meter: An irradiance unit which is equal to 1 watt of radiant power incident per one square meter surface area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_irradiance_unit
member.summary: irradiance unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the power of electromagnetic radiation at a surface, per unit area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_foot_candle
member.summary: foot candle: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 foot^[2]. One footcandle is equal to 10.76 lux.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_half_life
member.summary: half life: A time unit which represents the period over which the activity or concentration of a specified chemical or element falls to half its original activity or concentration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_century
member.summary: century: A time unit which is equal to 100 years.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_nanosecond
member.summary: nanosecond: A time unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a second or 10^[-9] s.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_counts_per_minute
member.summary: counts per minute: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the number of light emissions produced by ionizing radiation in one minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_disintegrations_per_minute
member.summary: disintegrations per minute: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per minute or there is one atom disintegration per minute.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_microcurie
member.summary: microcurie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one millionth of a curie or 10^[-6] Ci.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_millicurie
member.summary: millicurie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to one thousandth of a curie or 10^[-3] Ci.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_nanosievert
member.summary: nanosievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a sievert or 10^[-9] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_nanogray
member.summary: nanogray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a millionth of a gray or 10^[-9] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_milligray
member.summary: milligray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gray or 10^[-3] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_microgray
member.summary: microgray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to one millionth of a gray or 10^[-6] Gy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_Roentgen_equivalent_man
member.summary: Roentgen equivalent man: A dose equivalent unit which when multiplied by hundred is equal to one sievert or 1 Sv. 1 Sv is equal to 100 rem.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_microsievert
member.summary: microsievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one millionth of a sievert or 10^[-6] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_millisievert
member.summary: millisievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to one thousandth of a sievert or 10^[-3] Sv.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_sievert
member.summary: sievert: A dose equivalent unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_roentgen
member.summary: roentgen: An exposure unit which is equal to the amount of radiation required to liberate positive and negative charges of one electrostatic unit of charge in 1 cm^[3] of air at standard temperature and pressure (STP). This corresponds to the generation of approximately 2.0810^[9] ion pairs.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_rad
member.summary: rad: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to 0.01 gray (Gy).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_gray
member.summary: gray: An absorbed dose unit which is equal to the absorption of one joule of radiation energy by one kilogram of matter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_curie
member.summary: curie: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which there are 3.7 x 10^[10] atom disintegration per second (dps).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_becquerel
member.summary: becquerel: An activity (of a radionuclide) unit which is equal to the activity of a quantity of radioactive material in which one nucleus decays per second or there is one atom disintegration per second (dps).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_exposure_unit
member.summary: exposure unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the quantity that expresses the ability of radiation to ionize air and thereby create electric charges which can be collected and measured.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_dose_equivalent_unit
member.summary: dose equivalent unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the expression of dose in terms of its biological effect.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_absorbed_dose_unit
member.summary: absorbed dose unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the energy imparted by ionizing radiation to unit mass of matter such as tissue.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_activity__of_a_radionuclide__unit
member.summary: activity (of a radionuclide) unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the transformation (disintegration) rate of a radioactive substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radiation_unit
member.summary: radiation unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of radiation emitted by a given radiation source as well as the amount of radiation absorbed or deposited in a specific material by a radiation source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_steradian
member.summary: steradian: A solid angle unit which is equal to the solid angle subtended at the center of a sphere by an area on the surface of the sphere that is equal to the radius squared.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_solid_angle_unit
member.summary: solid angle unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by three or more planes intersecting at a common point.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radian
member.summary: radian: A plane angle unit which is equal to the angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc equal in length to the radius of the circle, approximately 57 degrees 17 minutes and 44.6 seconds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_plane_angle_unit
member.summary: plane angle unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the angle formed by two straight lines in the same plane.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_angle_unit
member.summary: angle unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the figure or space formed by the junction of two lines or planes.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_katal
member.summary: katal: A catalytic unit activity which is equal to the activity of a catalyst in moles per second, such as the amount of an enzyme needed to transform one mole of substrate per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_catalytic_activity_unit
member.summary: catalytic activity unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of the action of a catalyst.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_lumen
member.summary: lumen: A luminous flux unit which is equal to the luminous flux emitted into 1 steradian by a point source of 1 candela.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_luminous_flux_unit
member.summary: luminous flux unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the flow of radiant energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_lux
member.summary: lux: An illuminance unit which is equal to the illuminance produced by 1 lumen evenly spread over an area 1 m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_illuminance_unit
member.summary: illuminance unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the luminous flux incident on a unit area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_watt
member.summary: watt: A power unit which is equal to the power used when work is done at the rate of 1 joule per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_power_unit
member.summary: power unit: A unit which is a standard measure power or the rate of doing work.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_joule
member.summary: joule: An energy unit which is equal to the energy required when a force of 1 newton moves an object 1 meter in the direction of the force.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_energy_unit
member.summary: energy unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the work done by a certain force (gravitational, electric, magnetic, force of inertia, etc).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_pascal
member.summary: pascal: A pressure unit which is equal to the pressure or stress on a surface caused by a force of 1 newton spread over a surface of 1 m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_pressure_unit
member.summary: pressure unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the force applied to a given area.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_newton
member.summary: newton: A force unit which is equal to the force required to cause an acceleration of 1m/s2 of a mass of 1 Kg in the direction of the force.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_force_unit
member.summary: force unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the force is applied when a mass is accelerated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_hertz
member.summary: hertz: A frequency unit which is equal to 1 complete cycle of a recurring phenomenon in 1 second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_frequency_unit
member.summary: frequency unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the number of repetitive actions in a particular time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_femtoliter
member.summary: femtoliter: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-15] L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_picoliter
member.summary: picoliter: A volume unit which is equal to 10^[-12] L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_nanoliter
member.summary: nanoliter: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a liter or 10^[-9] L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_microliter
member.summary: microliter: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter or 10^[-6] L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_decimeter
member.summary: cubic decimeter: A volume unit which is equal to one thousand of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 L.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_liter
member.summary: liter: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 decimeter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_milliliter
member.summary: milliliter: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a liter or 10^[-3] L, or to 1 cubic centimeter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_centimeter
member.summary: cubic centimeter: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a cubic meter or 10^[-9] m^[3], or to 1 ml.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_meter
member.summary: cubic meter: A volume unit which is equal to the volume of a cube with edges one meter in length. One cubic meter equals to 1000 liters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_volume_unit
member.summary: volume unit: A unit which is a standard measure of the amount of space occupied by any substance, whether solid, liquid, or gas.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_meter_per_second
member.summary: meter per second: A speed/velocity unit which is equal to the speed of an object traveling 1 meter distance in one second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_meter_per_kilogram
member.summary: cubic meter per kilogram: A specific volume unit which is equal to one cubic meter volume occupied by one kilogram of a particular substance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_turns_per_second
member.summary: turns per second: A rotational frequency unit which is equal to the number complete turn in a period of time that equals to 1 second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_meter_per_second
member.summary: kilogram meter per second: A momentum unit which is equal to the momentum of a one kilogram mass object with a speed of one meter per second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_centimeter_per_mole
member.summary: cubic centimeter per mole: A molar volume unit which is equal to 1 cubic centimeter occupied by one mole of a substance in the form of a solid, liquid, or gas.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_cubic_meter_per_mole
member.summary: cubic meter per mole: A molar volume unit which is equal to 1 cubic meter occupied by one mole of a substance in the form of a solid, liquid, or gas.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_gram_per_mole
member.summary: gram per mole: A molar mass unit which is equal to one gram of mass of one mole of chemical element or chemical compound.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_mole
member.summary: kilogram per mole: A molar mass unit which is equal to one kilogram of mass of one mole of chemical element or chemical compound.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_square_meter
member.summary: kilogram per square meter: An area density unit which is equal to the mass of an object in kilograms divided by the surface area in meters squared.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_candela_per_square_meter
member.summary: candela per square meter: A luminance unit which is equal to a luminous intensity of one candela radiating from a surface whose area is one square meter.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_gram_per_cubic_centimeter
member.summary: gram per cubic centimeter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in grams divided by the volume in cubic centimeters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_kilogram_per_cubic_meter
member.summary: kilogram per cubic meter: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in kilograms divided by the volume in cubic meters.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_square_millimeter
member.summary: square millimeter: An area unit which is equal to one millionth of a square meter or 10^[-6] m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_square_centimeter
member.summary: square centimeter: An area unit which is equal to one ten thousandth of a square meter or 10^[-4] m^[2].

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_square_meter
member.summary: square meter: An area unit which is equal to an area enclosed by a square with sides each 1 meter long.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radian_per_second
member.summary: radian per second: An angular unit velocity which is equal to about 9.54930 rpm (revolutions per minute).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_radian_per_second_per_second
member.summary: radian per second per second: An angular unit acceleration which is equal to the angular acceleration of an object changing its angular velocity by 1rad/s over a time period that equals one second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_meter_per_second_per_second
member.summary: meter per second per second: An acceleration unit which is equal to the acceleration an object changing its velocity by 1meter/s over a time period that equals one second.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_mole_fraction
member.summary: mole fraction: A concentration unit which denotes the number of moles of solute as a proportion of the total number of moles in a solution.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_normal
member.summary: normal: A unit of concentration which is one gram equivalent of a solute per liter of solution. A gram equivalent weight or equivalent is a measure of the reactive capacity of a given molecule.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_unit_of_normality
member.summary: unit of normality: A unit of concentration which highlights the chemical nature of salts.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_femtomolar
member.summary: femtomolar: A unit of molarity which is equal to 10^[-15] M.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_picomolal
member.summary: picomolal: A molality unit which is equal to 10^[-12] m.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_nanomolal
member.summary: nanomolal: A molality unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a molal or 10^[-9] m.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_micromolal
member.summary: micromolal: A molality unit which is equal to one millionth of a molal or 10^[-6] m.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_millimolal
member.summary: millimolal: A molality unit which is equal to one thousandth of a molal or 10^[-3] m.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.UO_molal
member.summary: molal: A unit of concentration which expresses a concentration of a solution of 1 mole per kilogram of solvent (mol/kg).

member.summary: ion injection parameters: Tabular representation of the parameters around ion selection like the amount of time spent filling an ion trapping device for each scan acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_total_ion_currents
member.summary: total ion currents: Tabular representation of the total ion current detected in each of a series of mass spectra.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_identified_quantification_data_points
member.summary: number of identified quantification data points: The number of identified data points for quantification purposes within the run after user defined acceptance criteria are applied. These data points may be for example XIC profiles, isotopic pattern areas, or reporter ions (see MS:1001805). The used type should be noted in the metadata or analysis methods section of the recording file for the respective run. In case of multiple acceptance criteria (FDR) available in proteomics, PSM-level FDR should be used for better comparability.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_detected_quantification_data_points
member.summary: number of detected quantification data points: The number of data points detected for quantification purposes within the run. These data points may be for example XIC profiles, isotopic pattern areas, or reporter ions (see MS:1001805). The used type should be noted in the metadata or analysis methods section of the recording file for the respective run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_empty_MS3_scans
member.summary: number of empty MS3 scans: Number of MS3 scans where the scans' peaks intensity sums to 0 (i.e. no peaks or only 0-intensity peaks).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_empty_MS2_scans
member.summary: number of empty MS2 scans: Number of MS2 scans where the scans' peaks intensity sums to 0 (i.e. no peaks or only 0-intensity peaks).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_empty_MS1_scans
member.summary: number of empty MS1 scans: Number of MS1 scans where the scans' peaks intensity sums to 0 (i.e. no peaks or only 0-intensity peaks).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_signal_fall__10x__count
member.summary: MS1 signal fall (10x) count: The number of times where MS1 TIC decreased more than 10-fold between adjacent MS1 scans. An unusual high count of signal jumps or falls can indicate ESI stability issues.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_signal_jump__10x__count
member.summary: MS1 signal jump (10x) count: The number of times where MS1 TIC increased more than 10-fold between adjacent MS1 scans. An unusual high count of signal jumps or falls can indicate ESI stability issues.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_slowest_frequency_for_MS_level_2_collection
member.summary: slowest frequency for MS level 2 collection: The slowest acquisition speed with which product MS scans were collected. Scan acquisition frequency can be used to gauge the suitability of used instrument settings for the sample content used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_slowest_frequency_for_MS_level_1_collection
member.summary: slowest frequency for MS level 1 collection: The slowest acquisition speed with which precursor MS scans were collected. Scan acquisition frequency can be used to gauge the suitability of used instrument settings for the sample content used.

member.summary: QC non-metric term: QC terms associated but not directly metrics themselves.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC2_sample_intensities
member.summary: QC2 sample intensities: Observed intensities for the peptides of a QC2 sample measurement within 5 ppm and +/- 240 s RT tolerance. Different metrics of observed intensities are possible, at least one must be present. The table should contain the peptides as defined in the parent QC2 sample metric term, missing are interpreted as not detected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC2_sample_mass_accuracies
member.summary: QC2 sample mass accuracies: Observed mass accuracy for the peptides of a QC2 sample measurement. The table should contain the peptides as described in the QC2 sample metric term, missing are interpreted as not detected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC1_sample_metric
member.summary: QC1 sample metric: A QC metric based on the results of a QC1 sample measurement. A QC1 sample is made from trypsin-digested BSA MS Standard (CAM modified), see Pichler et al. Chiva et al. for details on QC sample design).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC2_sample_metric
member.summary: QC2 sample metric: A QC metric based on the results of a QC2 sample measurement. A QC2 sample is made from Pierce HeLa protein digest standard, see Pichler et al. Chiva et al. for details on QC sample design.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_low_complexity_QC_sample_metric

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_high_complexity_QC_sample_metric
member.summary: high complexity QC sample metric: A QC metric based on a QC sample of known and high complexity content.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC_sample_metric
member.summary: QC sample metric: A QC metric based on a QC sample of known content.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_observed_mass_accuracy
member.summary: observed mass accuracy: Observed mass accuracy in ppm, calculated by 1E6 x (observed m/z - theoretical m/z)/theoretical m/z of a selected and identified ion in a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_chromatograms
member.summary: number of chromatograms: The number of chromatograms recorded for the run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_retention_time_acquisition_range
member.summary: retention time acquisition range: Upper and lower limit of retention time at which spectra are recorded.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_m_z_acquisition_range
member.summary: m/z acquisition range: Upper and lower limit of m/z precursor values at which MSn spectra are recorded.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectra_half_TIC
member.summary: spectra half-TIC: The minimal proportion of peaks needed to account for at least 50% of the total ion current in each individual spectrum considered, recorded in a mandatory fraction column. Either USI or native spectrum identifier columns must be present as well.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_run_duration
member.summary: MS run duration: The duration of the mass spectrometry acquisition (as measured by the time between the last scan and first scan) in seconds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_Freq_Max
member.summary: MS2-Freq-Max: Fastest frequency for MS level 2 collection

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fastest_frequency_for_MS_level_2_collection
member.summary: fastest frequency for MS level 2 collection: Fastest frequency for MS level 2 collection

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_Freq_Max
member.summary: MS1-Freq-Max: Fastest frequency for MS level 1 collection

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fastest_frequency_for_MS_level_1_collection
member.summary: fastest frequency for MS level 1 collection: Fastest frequency for MS level 1 collection

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_unknown_and_likely_precursor_charges_fractions
member.summary: MS2 unknown and likely precursor charges fractions: The fractions of inferred charge state of MS/MS precursors. The fractions [0,1] are given in the 'Fraction' column, corresponding charges in the 'Charge state' column. Charge 0 represents unknown charge states.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_known_precursor_charges_fractions
member.summary: MS2 known precursor charges fractions: The fraction of MS/MS precursors of the corresponding charge. The fractions [0,1] are given in the 'Fraction' column, corresponding charges in the 'Charge state' column. The highest charge state is to be interpreted as that charge state or higher.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_peak_density_distribution___quantiles
member.summary: MS2 peak density distribution - quantiles: The first to n-th quantile of MS2 peak density (scan peak counts). A value triplet represents the original QuaMeter metrics, the quartiles of MS2 density. The number of values in the tuple implies the quantile mode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_density_quantiles
member.summary: MS2 density quantiles: The first to n-th quantile of MS2 peak density (scan peak counts). A value triplet represents the original QuaMeter metrics, the quartiles of MS2 density. The number of values in the tuple implies the quantile mode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_peak_density_distribution___quantiles
member.summary: MS1 peak density distribution - quantiles: The first to n-th quantile of MS1 peak density (scan peak counts). A value triplet represents the original QuaMeter metrics, the quartiles of MS1 density. The number of values in the tuple implies the quantile mode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_density_quantiles
member.summary: MS1 density quantiles: The first to n-th quantile of MS1 peak density (scan peak counts). A value triplet represents the original QuaMeter metrics, the quartiles of MS1 density. The number of values in the tuple implies the quantile mode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_Count
member.summary: MS2-Count: The number of MS2 events in the run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_MS2_spectra
member.summary: number of MS2 spectra: The number of MS2 events in the run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_Count
member.summary: MS1-Count: The number of MS1 events in the run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_MS1_spectra
member.summary: number of MS1 spectra: The number of MS1 events in the run.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_TIC_quartile_ratios
member.summary: MS1 TIC quartile ratios: The log ratios of successive TIC quartiles. The metric's value triplet represents the log ratios of TIC-Q2 to TIC-Q1, TIC-Q3 to TIC-Q2, TIC-max to TIC-Q3.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_TIC_change_quartile_ratios
member.summary: MS1 TIC-change quartile ratios: The log ratios of successive TIC-change quartiles. The TIC changes are the list of MS1 total ion current (TIC) value changes from one to the next scan, produced when each MS1 TIC is subtracted from the preceding MS1 TIC. The metric's value triplet represents the log ratio of the TIC-change Q2 to Q1, Q3 to Q2, TIC-change-max to Q3

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_quarter_RT_fraction
member.summary: MS2 quarter RT fraction: The interval used for acquisition of the first, second, third, and fourth quarter of all MS2 events divided by retention time duration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_quarter_RT_fraction
member.summary: MS1 quarter RT fraction: The interval used for acquisition of the first, second, third, and fourth quarter of all MS1 events divided by retention time duration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_TIC_quarters_RT_fraction
member.summary: TIC quarters RT fraction: The interval when the respective quarter of the TIC accumulates divided by retention time duration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_chromatography_duration
member.summary: chromatography duration: The retention time duration of the chromatography in seconds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_XIC_Height_quartile_ratios
member.summary: XIC-Height quartile ratios: The log ratio of successive XIC height quartiles. The metric's value triplet represents the log ratios of XIC-height-Q2 to XIC-height-Q1, XIC-height-Q3 to XIC-height-Q2, XIC-height max to XIC-height-Q3.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_XIC_FWHM_quantiles
member.summary: XIC-FWHM quantiles: The first to n-th quantile of peak widths for XICs. A metric's value triplet represents the related QuaMeter metrics of XIC-FWHM-Q1,Q2,Q3.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_XIC_WideFrac
member.summary: XIC-WideFrac: The number of XIC that account for the top half of all XIC-FWHM divided by the number of all XIC.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_XIC50_fraction
member.summary: XIC50 fraction: The number of XIC that account for the top half of all XIC-FWHM divided by the number of all XIC.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_environment_metric
member.summary: environment metric: QC metric related to measurements of the ambient environment, such as the laboratory.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_sample_preparation_metric
member.summary: sample preparation metric: QC metric related to the sample preparation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS2_metric
member.summary: MS2 metric: QC metric based on MS2 events.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS1_metric
member.summary: MS1 metric: QC metric based on MS1 events.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_source_metric
member.summary: ion source metric: QC metric related to events in the ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_metric
member.summary: MS metric: QC metric related to the mass spectrometry acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_XIC_metric
member.summary: XIC metric: QC metric related to an extracted ion chromatogram.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_chromatogram_metric
member.summary: chromatogram metric: QC metric related to a chromatogram.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_retention_time_metric
member.summary: retention time metric: QC metric related to retention time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_multiple_spectra_based_metric
member.summary: multiple spectra based metric: QC metric calculated from multiple spectra.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_single_spectrum_based_metric
member.summary: single spectrum based metric: QC metric calculated from a single spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_multiple_runs_based_metric
member.summary: multiple runs based metric: QC metric calculated from multiple runs (e.g. multiple .raw files).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_single_run_based_metric
member.summary: single run based metric: QC metric calculated from a single run (e.g. one .raw file).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_quantification_based_metric
member.summary: quantification based metric: QC metric based on quantification results.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ID_free_metric
member.summary: ID free metric: QC metric not based on identification results.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ID_based_metric
member.summary: ID based metric: QC metric based on identification results.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_QC_metric_category
member.summary: QC metric category: Categorization of the QC metric.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_matrix
member.summary: matrix: A matrix is a rectangular array of values of the same type (in contrast to a table). All values must be given a unit (e.g. UO:0000221 ! dalton or UO:0000187 ! percent), and optionally a type (e.g. STATO:0000574 ! median or MS:1002354 ! PSM-level q-value). All values in the matrix must have the same unit and type (if applicable).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_table
member.summary: table: Metrics consisting of a table or data frame. The values of the table may have different types in each column (in contrast to a matrix). Each column must have a unit (identical for all entries of this column) and may have a value type (e.g. STATO:0000574 ! median or MS:1002354 ! PSM-level q-value).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_n_tuple
member.summary: n-tuple: Metrics consisting of multiple values, with the number of values implicitly specified by length of the JSON array (e.g. length 4 for quartiles). All values must be given a unit (e.g. UO:0000221 ! dalton or UO:0000187 ! percent), and optionally a type (e.g. STATO:0000574 ! median or MS:1002354 ! PSM-level q-value). All values in the tuple must have the same unit and type (if applicable).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_single_value

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Lipid_empirical_score
member.summary: Lipid empirical score: The lipid empirical score is a point-based lipid class-specific scoring system based on MS and other evidence sources as defined by the Lipidomics Standards Initiative (LSI). The score has a numeric value between 0 and 100. Score values are lipid class-specific and are therefore not immediately comparable between lipid classes.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Lipid_shorthand_identification_confidence_level
member.summary: Lipid shorthand identification confidence level: Identification confidence levels based on the updated lipid shorthand nomenclature. The value slot can have the values 'Category', 'Class', 'Species', 'Phosphate-position', 'Molecular species', 'sn-position', 'DBE position', 'Structure defined', 'Full structure', 'Complete structure'.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Goslin
member.summary: Goslin: The Goslin implementations parse common lipid name dialects and normalize them to the recent lipid shorthand nomenclature based on grammars on succinct lipid nomenclature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectral_Pearson_correlation
member.summary: spectral Pearson correlation: The Pearson's rho statistic between a pair of points representing two vectorized spectra.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_normalized_spectral_angle
member.summary: normalized spectral angle: The angle subtended by two vectorized spectra in high-dimensional space. It is equal to the 1 - (2 * inverse cosine of the spectral dot product) / pi.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_shared_peak_count
member.summary: shared peak count: The number of peaks with closely matching m/z values that are common to two spectra.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectral_Euclidean_distance
member.summary: spectral Euclidean distance: The Euclidean distance between a pair of points representing two vectorized spectra in high-dimensional space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_cosine_similarity
member.summary: cosine similarity: The dot (inner) product of two vectorized spectra divided by the product of their vector norms. It ranges from 0 (orthogonal vectors) to 1 (collinear vectors). Also known as cosine similarity.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectral_dot_product
member.summary: spectral dot product: The dot (inner) product of two vectorized spectra divided by the product of their vector norms. It ranges from 0 (orthogonal vectors) to 1 (collinear vectors). Also known as cosine similarity.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectral_similarity
member.summary: spectral similarity: A measure of how similar two spectra are, based on the features of the spectra (the locations and intensities of peaks) alone.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SSM
member.summary: SSM: Result of a comparison of an observed fragment ion spectrum to another observed fragment ion spectrum, to assess the plausibility that two spectra originate from the same analyte, e.g., in spectral library searching and spectrum clustering.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectrum_spectrum_match
member.summary: spectrum-spectrum match: Result of a comparison of an observed fragment ion spectrum to another observed fragment ion spectrum, to assess the plausibility that two spectra originate from the same analyte, e.g., in spectral library searching and spectrum clustering.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_PSM
member.summary: PSM: Result of a comparison of an observed fragment ion spectrum to the theoretically predicted fragmentation pattern of a peptide sequence, to assess the plausibility that the observed spectrum originates from the putative peptide sequence.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_peptide_spectrum_match
member.summary: peptide-spectrum match: Result of a comparison of an observed fragment ion spectrum to the theoretically predicted fragmentation pattern of a peptide sequence, to assess the plausibility that the observed spectrum originates from the putative peptide sequence.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spectrum_match
member.summary: spectrum match: Result of a comparison of a spectrum to another spectrum, usually to assess the plausibility that the two spectra originate from the same analyte.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_contributing_replicate_spectrum_USI
member.summary: contributing replicate spectrum USI: A list of cross references to contributing replicate spectra, in the form of PSI Universal Spectrum Identifiers.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_contributing_replicate_spectrum_keys
member.summary: contributing replicate spectrum keys: A list of cross references to contributing replicate spectra in the same library, in the form of library spectrum keys.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_contributing_replicate_spectrum
member.summary: contributing replicate spectrum: A cross reference to another spectrum that is a replicate spectrum of the same analyte and contributes to the generation of this aggregated spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_replicates_spectra_used_from_source
member.summary: number of replicates spectra used from source: The number of replicate spectra used during the aggregation process that originate from a specified source (e.g. a file, a dataset, a sample type, etc.). This term must appear in a group alongside a source term, which is one of: 'ProteomeXchange accession number', 'constituent spectrum file', or 'sample name'

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_summary_statistics_of_replicates
member.summary: summary statistics of replicates: Summary statistics of an attribute among all replicates that are aggregated to generate this spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_activated_dissociation
member.summary: electron activated dissociation: A process to fragment ions in a high intensity electron beam which results in a dissociation of various analytes ranging from singly charged small molecules to multiply protonated proteins.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_number_of_unassigned_peaks

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Bruker_TSF_format
member.summary: Bruker TSF format: Bruker TSF raw file format.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_library_spectrum_name

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_intermediate_PSM_list
member.summary: intermediate PSM list: A flag on a list of PSMs (SpectrumIdentificationList) to indicate that this is not the final set of identifications to be interpreted by consuming software. This term should be used when results are provided from multiple search engines for the results from each search engine before they are combined to give consensus identifications. Amongst the set of SpectrumIdentificationList(s) that are flagged with the term, each spectrum may be referenced from more than one SpectrumIdentificationResult.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_final_PSM_list

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Byonic_Peptide_LogProb
member.summary: Byonic:Peptide LogProb: The log p-value of the PSM. This is the log of the probability that the PSM with such a score and delta would arise by chance in a search of this size (the size of the protein database, as expanded by the modification rules). A log p-value of -3.0 should happen by chance on only one of a thousand spectra. Caveat: it is very hard to compute a p-value that works for all searches and all spectra, so read Byonic p-values with a certain amount of skepticism.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Byonic_PEP
member.summary: Byonic:PEP: Byonic posterior error probability.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Byonic_DeltaMod_Score
member.summary: Byonic:DeltaMod Score: The drop in Byonic score from the top-scoring peptide to the next peptide different in any way, including placement of modifications. DeltaMod gives an indication of whether modifications are confidently localized; DeltaMod over 10.0 means that there is high likelihood that all modification placements are correct.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Byonic_Delta_Score
member.summary: Byonic:Delta Score: The drop in Byonic score from the top-scoring peptide to the next peptide with distinct sequence. In this computation, the same peptide with different modifications is not considered distinct.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Byonic_Score
member.summary: Byonic:Score: The Byonic score is the primary indicator of PSM correctness. The Byonic score reflects the absolute quality of the peptide-spectrum match, not the relative quality compared to other candidate peptides. Byonic scores range from 0 to about 1000, with 300 a good score, 400 a very good score, and PSMs with scores over 500 almost sure to be correct.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_ShowDecoyMatches
member.summary: Mascot:ShowDecoyMatches: If true, then the search results are against an automatically generated decoy database and the reported peptide matches and protein hits come from the decoy database. Otherwise peptide matches and protein hits come from the original database.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_IncludeErrorTolerantMatches
member.summary: Mascot:IncludeErrorTolerantMatches: If true, then the search results are error tolerant and peptide matches from the second pass are included in search results. Otherwise no error tolerant peptide matches are included.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_UseUnigeneClustering
member.summary: Mascot:UseUnigeneClustering: If true, then the search results are against a nucleic acid database and Unigene clustering is enabled. Otherwise UniGene clustering is not in use.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_RequireBoldRed
member.summary: Mascot:RequireBoldRed: Only used in Peptide Summary and Select Summary reports. If true, a peptide match must be 'bold red' to be included in the report; bold red means the peptide is a top ranking match in a query and appears for the first time (in linear order) in the list of protein hits.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_ShowHomologousProteinsWithSubsetOfPeptides
member.summary: Mascot:ShowHomologousProteinsWithSubsetOfPeptides: If true, show (sequence or spectrum) sub-set and subsumable proteins. Otherwise they are suppressed.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_ShowHomologousProteinsWithSamePeptides
member.summary: Mascot:ShowHomologousProteinsWithSamePeptides: If true, show (sequence or spectrum) same-set proteins. Otherwise they are suppressed.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_MinMSMSThreshold
member.summary: Mascot:MinMSMSThreshold: Mascot peptide match ion score threshold. If between 0 and 1, then peptide matches whose expect value exceeds the thresholds are suppressed; if at least 1, then peptide matches whose ion score is below the threshold are suppressed.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_ProteinScoringMethod
member.summary: Mascot:ProteinScoringMethod: Mascot protein scoring method; either 'Standard' or 'MudPIT'.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_MaxProteinHits
member.summary: Mascot:MaxProteinHits: The number of protein hits to display in the report. If 'Auto', all protein hits that have a protein score exceeding the average peptide identity threshold are reported. Otherwise an integer at least 1.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Mascot_SigThreshold
member.summary: Mascot:SigThreshold: Significance threshold below which the p-value of a peptide match must lie to be considered statistically significant (default 0.05).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_LOWESS_smoothing
member.summary: LOWESS smoothing: Reduces intensity spikes by applying a modelling method known as locally weighted polynomial regression. At each point in the data set a low-degree polynomial is fit to a subset of the data, with explanatory variable values near the point whose response is being estimated. The polynomial is fit using weighted least squares, giving more weight to points near the point whose response is being estimated and less weight to points further away. The value of the regression function for the point is then obtained by evaluating the local polynomial using the explanatory variable values for that data point. The LOESS fit is complete after regression function values have been computed for each of the n data points. Many of the details of this method, such as the degree of the polynomial model and the weights, are flexible.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Savitzky_Golay_smoothing
member.summary: Savitzky-Golay smoothing: Reduces intensity spikes by applying local polynomial regression (of degree k) on a distribution (of at least k+1 equally spaced points) to determine the smoothed value for each point. It tends to preserve features of the distribution such as relative maxima, minima and width, which are usually 'flattened' by other adjacent averaging techniques.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_selected_reaction_monitoring_spectrum
member.summary: selected reaction monitoring spectrum: Spectrum obtained when data are acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z values of selected precursor ions a recorded via two or more stages of mass spectrometry. The precursor/product ion pair is called a transition pair. Data can be obtained for a single transition pair or multiple transition pairs. Multiple time segments of different transition pairs can exist in a single file. Single precursor ions can have multiple product ions consitituting multiple transition pairs. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed as tandem mass spectrometry in time or tandem mass spectrometry in space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_orbitrap
member.summary: orbitrap: An ion trapping device that consists of an outer barrel-like electrode and a coaxial inner spindle-like electrode that form an electrostatic field with quadro-logarithmic potential distribution. The frequency of harmonic oscillations of the orbitally trapped ions along the axis of the electrostatic field is independent of the ion velocity and is inversely proportional to the square root of m/z so that the trap can be used as a mass analyzer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6410_Triple_Quad_LC_MS
member.summary: 6410 Triple Quad LC/MS: The 6410 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a Agilent triple quadrupole mass spectrometer. Mass range of the mass spectrometer is 15-1650 m/z, resolution is at three settings of 0.7 u (unit), 1.2 u (wide) and 2.5 u (widest). The mass accuracy for 6410 mass spectrometer is 0.1 across the mass range. The collision cell is a hexapole with linear acceleration.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6210_Time_of_Flight_LC_MS
member.summary: 6210 Time-of-Flight LC/MS: The 6210 Time-of-Flight LC/MS is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a Agilent time of flight mass spectrometer. This time of flight mass spectrometer has a m/z range of 50-12000, mass accuracy of less than 2 ppm and resolution greater than 13,000 at m/z 2722. It has multiple ion sources and can be used with multimode ion sources.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6140_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6140 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6140 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with a single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 Series of Agilent quadrupole mass spectrometers. 6140 Quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 10-1350, 2500 u/s scan speed in standard mode and 10000 u/s speed in fast-scan mode. It also uses multiple signal acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6130_Quadrupole_LC_MS

The 6130 quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 2-3000, 2500 u/s scan speed in standard mode and 5250 u/s speed in fast-scan mode. It also uses multiple signal acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6120A_Quadrupole_LC_MS

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_6110_Quadrupole_LC_MS
member.summary: 6110 Quadrupole LC/MS: The 6110 Quadrupole LC/MS system is a Agilent liquid chromatography instrument combined with an entry level single quadrupole mass spectrometer from the 6100 Series of Agilent quadrupole mass spectrometers. 6110 Quadrupole mass spectrometer has m/z range of 10-1500 and 2500 u/s scan speed. It proves useful for wide range of SIM quantitative applications.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_unimolecular_dissociation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: unimolecular dissociation: Fragmentation reaction in which the molecularity is treated as one, irrespective of whether the dissociative state is that of a metastable ion produced in the ion source or results from collisional excitation of a stable ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_surface_induced_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: surface-induced reaction: A process wherein a reactant ion interacts with a surface to produce either chemically different species or a change in the internal energy of the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_superelastic_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: superelastic collision: Collision in which the translational energy of the fast-moving collision partner is increased at the expense of internal energy of one or both collision partners.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion reaction: Chemical transformation involving an ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_partial_charge_transfer_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: partial charge transfer reaction: Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some but not all of the ion charge is transferred to the neutral.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MPD
member.summary: MPD: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_multiphoton_dissociation
member.summary: multiphoton dissociation: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_photodissociation
member.summary: photodissociation: A process wherein the reactant ion is dissociated as a result of absorption of one or more photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_McLafferty_Rearrangement_OBSOLETE
member.summary: McLafferty Rearrangement: A dissociation reaction triggered by transfer of a hydrogen atom via a 6-member transition state to the formal radical/charge site from a carbon atom four atoms removed from the charge/radical site (the gamma-carbon); subsequent rearrangement of electron density leads to expulsion of an olefin molecule. This term was originally applied to ketone ions where the charge/radical site is the carbonyl oxygen, but it is now more widely applied.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_low_energy_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: low-energy collision-induced dissociation: A collision-induced dissociation process wherein the precursor ion has the translational energy lower than approximately 1000 eV. This process typically requires multiple collisions and the collisional excitation is cumulative.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_low_energy_collisions_OBSOLETE
member.summary: low energy collisions: A collision between an ion and neutral species with translational energy approximately 1000 eV or lower.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_kinetic_method_OBSOLETE
member.summary: kinetic method: An approach to determination of ion thermodynamic quantities by a bracketing procedure in which the relative probabilities of competing ion fragmentations are measured via the relative abundances of the reaction products. The extended kinetic method takes the associated entropy changes into account.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_exchange_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion/neutral species exchange reaction: In this reaction an association reaction is accompanied by the subsequent or simultaneous liberation of a different neutral species as a product.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_species_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion/neutral species reaction: A process wherein a charged species interacts with a neutral reactant to produce either chemically different species or changes in the internal energy of one or both of the reactants.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_neutral_complex_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion/neutral complex: A particular type of transition state that lies between precursor and product ions on the reaction coordinate of some ion reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_molecule_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion/molecule reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral molecule. The term ion-molecule reaction is not recommended because the hyphen suggests a single species that is that is both an ion and a molecule.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ionizing_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ionizing collision: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which one or more electrons are removed from either the ion or neutral.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_energy_loss_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion energy loss spectrum: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function their loss of translational energy in reactions with neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_hydrogen_deuterium_exchange_OBSOLETE
member.summary: hydrogen/deuterium exchange: Exchange of hydrogen atoms with deuterium atoms in a molecule or pre-formed ion in solution prior to introduction into a mass spectrometer, or by reaction of an ion with a deuterated collision gas inside a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_homolytic_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: homolytic cleavage: Fragmentation of an odd electron ion that results from one of a pair of electrons that form a bond between two atoms moving to form a pair with the odd electron on the atom at the apparent charge site. Fragmentation results in the formation of an even electron ion and a radical. This reaction involves the movement of a single electron and is symbolized by a single-barbed arrow. Synonymous with Homolysis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_HCD
member.summary: HCD: A collision-induced dissociation process that occurs in a beam-type collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_beam_type_collision_induced_dissociation
member.summary: beam-type collision-induced dissociation: A collision-induced dissociation process that occurs in a beam-type collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_high_energy_collision_OBSOLETE
member.summary: high energy collision: Collision-induced dissociation process wherein the projectile ion has laboratory-frame translational energy higher than 1 keV.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_heterolytic_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: heterolytic cleavage: Fragmentation of a molecule or ion in which both electrons forming the single bond that is broken remain on one of the atoms that were originally bonded. This term is synonymous with heterolysis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_collision_gas
member.summary: collision gas: An inert gas used for collisional excitation. The term target gas is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_collisional_excitation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: collisional excitation: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_transfer_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge transfer reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which some or all of the charge of the reactant ion is transferred to the neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_stripping_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge stripping reaction: Reaction of a positive ion with a neutral species in which the positive charge on the product ion is greater than that on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_permutation_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge permutation reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species with a resulting change in the magnitude or sign of the charge on the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge inversion reaction: Reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the charge on the product ion is reversed in sign with respect to the reactant ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_induced_fragmentation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge-induced fragmentation: Fragmentation of an odd electron ion in which the cleaved bond is adjacent to the apparent charge site. Synonymous with charge mediated fragmentation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_buffer_gas
member.summary: buffer gas: An inert gas used for collisional deactivation of internally excited ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_beta_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: beta-cleavage: A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at an atom removed from the apparent charge site atom by two bonds and an atom adjacent to that atom and removed from the aparent charge site by three bonds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_alpha_cleavage_OBSOLETE
member.summary: alpha-cleavage: A homolytic cleavage where the bond fission occurs between at the atom adjacent to the atom at the apparent charge site and an atom removed from the aparent charge site by two bonds.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_association_reaction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: association reaction: The reaction of an ion with a neutral species in which the reactants combine to form a single ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_vertical_ionization
member.summary: vertical ionization: A process in which an electron is removed from or added to a molecule without a change in the positions of the atoms. The resulting ion is typically in an excited vibrational state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_thermal_ionization
member.summary: thermal ionization: The ionization of a neutral species through contact with a high temperature surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_surface_ionization
member.summary: surface ionization: The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_surface_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: surface-assisted laser desorption ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions from molecules that are deposited on a particular surface substrate that is irradiated with a pulsed laser. See also matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_spark_ionization
member.summary: spark ionization: The formation of ions from a solid material by an intermittent electrical discharge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_soft_ionization
member.summary: soft ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions without extensive fragmentation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_secondary_ionization
member.summary: secondary ionization: The process in which ions are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms or ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_pre_ionization_state_OBSOLETE
member.summary: pre-ionization state: An electronic state capable of undergoing auto-Ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_plasma_desorption_ionization
member.summary: plasma desorption ionization: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_penning_ionization
member.summary: penning ionization: Ionization that occurs through the interaction of two or more neutral gaseous species, at least one of which is internally excited.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nanospray
member.summary: nanospray: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nanoelectrospray
member.summary: nanoelectrospray: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_microelectrospray
member.summary: microelectrospray: Electrospray ionization at a solvent flow rate of 300-800 nL/min where the flow is a result of a mechanical pump. See nanoelectrospray.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_membrane_inlet
member.summary: membrane inlet: A semi-permeable membrane separator that permits the passage of gas sample directly to the mass spectrometer ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_liquid_secondary_ionization
member.summary: liquid secondary ionization: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of ions with a sample that is dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also fast atom bombardment and secondary ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: laser desorption ionization: The formation of gas-phase ions by the interaction of a pulsed laser with a solid or liquid material.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ionization_efficiency
member.summary: ionization efficiency: The ratio of the number of ions formed to the number of electrons, molecules or photons used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_pair_formation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion-pair formation: The reaction of a molecule to form both a positive ion and negative ion fragment among the products.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_desolvation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion desolvation: The removal of solvent molecules clustered around a gas-phase ion by means of heating and/or collisions with gas molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_ionization
member.summary: electron ionization: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_dissociative_ionization
member.summary: dissociative ionization: The reaction of a gas-phase molecule that results in its decomposition to form products, one of which is an ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_desorption_ionization_on_silicon
member.summary: desorption/ionization on silicon: The formation of ions by laser desorption ionization of a sample deposited on a porous silicon surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_chemi_ionization
member.summary: chemi-ionization: The reaction of a neutral molecule with an internally excited molecule to form an ion. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemical ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_exchange_ionization
member.summary: charge exchange ionization: The interaction of an ion with an atom or molecule in which the charge on the ion is transferred to the neutral without the dissociation of either. Synonymous with charge transfer ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_autoionization
member.summary: autoionization: The formation of an ion when an atom or molecule in a discrete state with an energy greater than the ionization threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_autodetachment
member.summary: autodetachment: The formation of a neutral when a negative ion in a discrete state with an energy greater than the detachment threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_photoionization
member.summary: atmospheric pressure photoionization: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_associative_ionization
member.summary: associative ionization: An ionization process in which two excited atoms or molecules react to form a single positive ion and an electron.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_adiabatic_ionization
member.summary: adiabatic ionization: A process whereby an electron is removed from an atom, ion, or molecule to produce an ion in its lowest energy state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_unstable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: unstable ion: An ion with sufficient energy to dissociate within the ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_stable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: stable ion: An ion with internal energy sufficiently low that it does not rearrange or dissociate prior to detection in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_reference_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: reference ion: A stable ion whose structure is known with certainty. These ions are usually formed by direct ionization of a neutral molecule of known structure and are used to verify by comparison the structure of an unknown ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_radical_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: radical ion: An ion, either a cation or anion, containing unpaired electrons in its ground state. The unpaired electron is denoted by a superscript dot alongside the superscript symbol for charge, such as for the molecular ion of a molecule M, that is, M+. Radical ions with more than one charge and/or more than one unpaired electron are denoted such as M(2+)(2). Unless the positions of the unpaired electron and charge can be associated with specific atoms, superscript charge designation should be placed before the superscript dot designation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_protonated_molecule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: protonated molecule: An ion formed by interaction of a neutral molecule with a proton and represented by the symbol [M + H]+, where M is the neutral molecule. The term 'protonated molecular ion,' 'quasi-molecular ion' and 'pseudo-molecular ion' are not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_positive_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: positive ion: An atomic or molecular species having a net positive electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_principal_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: principal ion: Most abundant ion of an isotope cluster, such as the 11B79Br2 81Br+ ion of m/z 250 of the cluster of isotopologue molecular ions of BBr3. The term principal ion has also been used to describe ions that have been artificially isotopically enriched in one or more positions such as CH3 13CH3+ or CH2D2 +, but those are best defined as isotopologue ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_onium_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: onium ion: A positively charged hypervalent ion of the nonmetallic elements. Examples are the methonium ion CH5+, the hydrogenonium ion H3+ and the hydronium ion H3O+. Other examples are the carbonium, oxonium, sulfonium, nitronium, diazonium, phosphonium, and halonium ions. Onium ions are not limited to monopositive ions; multiply-charged onium ions exist such as the gitonic (proximal) oxonium dication H4O2+ and the distonic oxonium dication H2O+-CH2-CH2-OH2+.
