member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_non_classical_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: non-classical ion: Hyper-coordinated carbonium ion such as the penta-coordinated norbornyl cation. Note: Tri-coordinated carbenium ions are termed classical ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_negative_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: negative ion: An atomic or molecular species having a net negative electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_molecular_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: molecular ion: An ion formed by the removal of one or more electrons to form a positive ion or the addition off one or more electrons to form a negative ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_metastable_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: metastable ion: An ion that is formed with internal energy higher than the threshold for dissociation but with a lifetime great enough to allow it to exit the ion source and enter the mass spectrometer where it dissociates before detection.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Isotopomeric_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Isotopomeric ion: Isomeric ion having the same numbers of each isotopic atom but differing in their positions. Isotopomeric ions can be either configurational isomers in which two atomic isotopes exchange positions or isotopic stereoisomers. The term isotopomer is a shortening of isotopic isomer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Isotopologue_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Isotopologue ion: An ion that differs only in the isotopic composition of one or more of its constituent atoms. For example CH4+ and CH3D+ or 10BF3 and 11BF3. The term isotopologue is a contraction of isotopic homologue.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion__OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion?: An atomic or molecular species having a net positive or negative electric charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fragment_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: fragment ion: A product ion that results from the dissociation of a precursor ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_enium_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: enium ion: A positively charged lower-valency ion of the nonmetallic elements. The methenium ion is CH3+. Other examples are the oxenium, sulfenium, nitrenium, phosphenium, and halenium ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_distonic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: distonic ion: A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin cannot be both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms as it can be with a conventional ion. For example, CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion whereas the radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+ is a conventional ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_dimeric_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: dimeric ion: An ion formed by ionization of a dimer or by the association of an ion with its neutral counterpart such as [M2]+ or [M-H-M]+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_diagnostic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: diagnostic ion: A product ion whose formation reveals structural or compositional information of its precursor. For instance, the phenyl cation in an electron ionization mass spectrum is a diagnostic ion for benzene and derivatives.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Conventional_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Conventional ion: A radical cation or anion in which the charge site and the unpaired electron spin are both formally located in the same atom or group of atoms, as opposed to the spatially separate electronic configuration of distonic ions. The radical cation of methanol, CH3OH+, in which the charge and spin sites are formally located at the O atom is an example of a conventional ion, whereas .CH2-OH2+ is a distonic ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_cluster_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: cluster ion: An ion formed by a multi-component atomic or molecular assembly of one or more ions with atoms or molecules, such as [(H20)nH]+, [(NaCl)nNa]+ and [(H3PO3)nHPO3]-.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_cationized_molecule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: cationized molecule: An ion formed by the association of a cation with a neutral molecule, M, for example [M+ Na]+ and [M + K]+. The terms quasi-molecular ion and pseudo-molecular ion should not be used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_anti_aromatic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: anti-aromatic ion: A planar cyclic ion with 4n ? electrons and is therefore not aromatic.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_analog_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: analog ion: Ions that have similar chemical valence, for example the acetyl cation CH3-CO+ and the thioacetyl cation CH3-CS+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_aromatic_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: aromatic ion: A planar cyclic ion that obeys the Hueckel (4n + 2) rule where n is a positive integer representing the number of conjugated Pi electrons. Charge delocalization leads to greater stability compared to a hypothetical localized structure.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_adduct_ion
member.summary: adduct ion: Ion formed by the interaction of an ion with one or more atoms or molecules to form an ion containing all the constituent atoms of the precursor ion as well as the additional atoms from the associated atoms or molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_secondary_electron_OBSOLETE
member.summary: secondary electron: Electrons that are ejected from a sample surface as a result of bombardment by a primary beam of atoms, ions or photons. WAS IN DETECTOR TYPE. Where should it go.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_postacceleration_detector
member.summary: postacceleration detector: A detector in which the charged particles are accelerated to a high velocity and impinge on a conversion dynode, emitting secondary electrons. The electrons are accelerated onto a phosphor screen, which emits photons that are in turn detected using a photomultiplier or other photon detector.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_point_collector
member.summary: point collector: A detector in which the ion beam is focused onto a point and the individual ions arrive sequentially.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_to_photon_detector
member.summary: ion-to-photon detector: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn strike a phosphor and the resulting photons are detected by a photomultiplier.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_focal_plane_collector
member.summary: focal plane collector: A detector for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_dynode
member.summary: dynode: One of a series of electrodes in a photomultiplier tube. Such an arrangement is able to amplify the current emitted by the photocathode.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_conversion_dynode
member.summary: conversion dynode: A surface that is held at high potential such that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_array_detector
member.summary: array detector: Detector comprising several ion collection elements, arranged in a line or grid where each element is an individual detector.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Progeny_Fragment_Ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Progeny Fragment Ion: A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_progeny_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: progeny ion: A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: product ion spectrum: A mass spectrum recorded from any spectrometer in which the appropriate m/z separation scan function is set to record the product ion or ions of selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_product_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: product ion: An ion formed as the product of a reaction involving a particular precursor ion. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation to form fragment ions, an ion/molecule reaction, or simply involve a change in the number of charges. The term fragment ion is deprecated. The term daughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_precursor_ion_spectrum
member.summary: precursor ion spectrum: Spectrum generated by scanning precursor m/z while monitoring a fixed product m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_precursor_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: precursor ion: An ion that reacts to form particular product ions. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation, ion/molecule reaction, isomerization, or change in charge state. The term parent ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nth generation product ion spectrum: The mass spectrum recorded from any mass spectrometer in which the appropriate scan function can be set to record the appropriate generation product ion or ions of m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nth generation product ion scan: The specific scan functions or processes that record the appropriate generation of product ion or ions of any m/z selected precursor ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nth_generation_product_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nth generation product ion: Serial product ions from dissociation of selected precursor ions where n refers to the number of stages of dissociation. The term granddaughter ion is deprecated.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_neutral_loss
member.summary: neutral loss: The loss of an uncharged species during a rearrangement process. The value slot holds the molecular formula in Hill notation of the neutral loss molecule, see PMID: 21182243. This term must be used in conjunction with a child of the term MS:1002307 (fragmentation ion type).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Space_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MS/MS in Space: A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in m/z analyzers separated in space. Specific m/z separation functions are designed such that in one section of the instrument ions are selected, dissociated in an intermediate region, and the product ions are then transmitted to another analyser for m/z separation and data acquisition.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_MS_in_Time_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MS/MS in Time: A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in a single m/z analyzer (such as a Paul Ion Trap or FTMS) in discreet steps over time. Ions in a specific m/z range are selected, dissociated, and the product ions analyzed sequentially in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B_1__E_E0___1_2___E_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant B[1-(E/E0)]^1/2 / E: A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector placed in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed while scanning the magnetic field, B, and electric field, E, simultaneously, so as to maintain the quantity B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a constant neutral mass loss (or gain) spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors. E0 is the electric field required to transmit the singly charged analog of the desired neutral fragment. The term B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E linked scan.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_B2_E_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant B2/E: A linked scan performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed and the magnetic field, B, and the electric field, E, are scanned simultaneously so as to maintain the ratio B2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a precursor ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in the field free region preceding the two sectors. The term B2/E linked scan is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Linked_Scan_at_Constant_E2_V_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Linked Scan at Constant E2/V: A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector. The electric sector field, E, and the accelerating voltage, V, are scanned simultaneously, so as to maintain the ratio E2/V at a constant value. This linked scan recordss a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region (FFR) preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_linked_scan_at_constant_b_e_OBSOLETE
member.summary: linked scan at constant b/e: A linked scan at constant B/E may be performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector. The magnetic field B and the electric field E are scanned simultaneously while the accelerating voltage V is held constant, so as to maintain the ratio of the two fields constant. This linked scan may record a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_linked_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: linked scan: A scan in an instrument with two or more m/z analysers or in a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector and one electric sector. Two or more of the analyzers are scanned simultaneously so as to preserve a predetermined relationship between scan parameters to produce a product ion, precursor ion or constant neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_e_2_mass_spectrum
member.summary: e/2 mass spectrum: A mass spectrum obtained using a sector mass spectrometer in which the electric sector field E is set to half the value required to transmit the main ion-beam. This spectrum records the signal from doubly charged product ions of charge-stripping reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_consecutive_reaction_monitoring_OBSOLETE_1000327
member.summary: consecutive reaction monitoring: A type of MS2 experiments with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_mass_loss_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral mass loss spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral loss spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_mass_gain_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral mass gain spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_spectrum
member.summary: constant neutral gain spectrum: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Constant_Neutral_Mass_Gain_Scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Constant Neutral Mass Gain Scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_gain_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: constant neutral gain scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_constant_neutral_loss_scan_OBSOLETE
member.summary: constant neutral loss scan: Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z decrement.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_inversion_mass_spectrum
member.summary: charge inversion mass spectrum: The measurement of the relative abundance of ions that result from a charge inversion reaction as a function of m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_2E_Mass_Spectrum_OBSOLETE
member.summary: 2E Mass Spectrum: A mass spectrum obtained by setting the electric sector field E to twice the value required to transmit the main ion-beam thereby allowing ions with a kinetic energy-to-charge ratio twice that of the main ion-beam to be transmitted. Product ions resulting from partial charge transfer reactions such as m^2+ + N ? m^+ + N^+ that occur in a collision cell (containing a gas, N) located in a field-free region preceding a magnetic and electric sector combination are detected. When the magnetic sector field B is scanned, a mass spectrum of singly charged product ions of doubly charged precursor ions is obtained.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_static_field
member.summary: static field: An electric or magnetic field that does not change in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_space_charge_effect
member.summary: space charge effect: The mutual repulsion of particles of like charge that limits the current in a charged-particle beam and causes beams or packets of charged particles to expand radially over time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_resonance_ion_ejection_OBSOLETE
member.summary: resonance ion ejection: A mode of ion ejection in a quadrupole ion trap that relies on a auxiliary radio frequency voltage that is applied to the end-cap electrodes. The voltage is tuned to the secular frequency of a particular ion to eject it.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_orthogonal_extraction_OBSOLETE
member.summary: orthogonal extraction: The pulsed acceleration of ions perpendicular to their direction of travel into a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. Ions may be extracted from a directional ion source, drift tube or m/z separation stage.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mathieu_stability_diagram_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mathieu stability diagram: A graphical representation expressed in terms of reduced coordinates that describes charged particle motion in a quadrupole mass filter or quadrupole ion trap mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_selective_instability_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass selective instability: A method for selective ejection of ions according to their m/z value in an ion trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_selective_axial_ejection_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass selective axial ejection: The use of mass selective instability to eject ions of selected m/z values from an ion trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_scan_m_z_range__OBSOLETE
member.summary: scan m/z range?: The limit of m/z over which a mass spectrometer can detect ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_limit_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass limit: The m/z value above which ions cannot be detected in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_kinetic_energy_analyzer
member.summary: kinetic energy analyzer: A device for measuring the kinetic energy of charged particles using a retarding field, time-of-flight, or the extent of deflection in an electric or magnetic field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fringing_field
member.summary: fringing field: The electric or magnetic field that extends from the edge of a sector, lens or other ion optics element.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_first_stability_region
member.summary: first stability region: The region of a Mathieu stability diagram closest to the origin. Ions within this region can traverse the full length of a transmission quadrupole.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electric_field_strength
member.summary: electric field strength: The magnitude of the force per unit charge at a given point in space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_einzel_lens
member.summary: einzel lens: Three element charged particle lens in which the first and third elements are held at the same voltage. Such a lens produces focusing without changing the translational energy of the particle.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_dynamic_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: dynamic mass spectrometry: A mass spectrometer in which m/z separation using one or more electric fields that vary with time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_cyclotron_motion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: cyclotron motion: The circular motion of a charged particle moving at velocity v in a magnetic field B that results from the force qvB.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_accelerating_voltage
member.summary: accelerating voltage: The electrical potential used to impart kinetic energy to ions in a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_transmission_quadrupole_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: transmission quadrupole mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_tandem_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: tandem mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer designed for mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_sector_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: sector mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer consisting of one or more magnetic sectors for m/z selection in a beam of ions. Such instruments may also have one or more electric sectors for energy selection.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_reflectron
member.summary: reflectron: A time-of-flight mass spectrometer that uses a static electric field to reverse the direction of travel of the ions entering it. A reflectron improves mass resolution by assuring that ions of the same m/z but different kinetic energy arrive at the detector at the same time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_quistor_OBSOLETE
member.summary: quistor: An abbreviation of quadrupole ion storage trap. This term is synonymous with Paul Ion Trap. If so then add a synonym to paul and obsolete this term.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_prolate_traochoidal_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: prolate traochoidal mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer in which the ions of different m/z are separated by means of crossed electric and magnetic fields in such a way that the selected ions follow a prolate trochoidal path.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_paul_ion_trap_OBSOLETE
member.summary: paul ion trap: A device that permits the trapping of ions by means of an alternating current voltage. The ejection of ions with a m/z less than a prescribed value and retention of those with higher mass depends on the application of radio frequency voltages between a ring electrode and two end-cap electrodes to confine the ions in a circular path. The choice of these voltages determines the m/z below which ions are ejected.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nier_johnson_geometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nier-johnson geometry: An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/2 radians in a radial electric field analyzer is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/3 radians.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mattauch_herzog_geometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mattauch-herzog geometry: An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/(4 ?(2)) radians in a radial electric field is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/2 radians.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_spectrum
member.summary: mass spectrum: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass spectrometer: An instrument that measures the mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundances of ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_spectrograph_obsolete_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass spectrograph obsolete: An instrument that separates a beam of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio in which the ions are directed onto a focal plane detector such as a photographic plate.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_linear_ion_trap
member.summary: linear ion trap: A two dimensional Paul ion trap in which ions are confined in the axial dimension by means of an electric field at the ends of the trap.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_hybrid_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: hybrid mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that combines m/z analyzers of different types to perform tandem mass spectrometry.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_double_focusing_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: double-focusing mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer that uses a magnetic sector for m/z focusing and an electric sector for energy focusing of an ion beam.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_cyclotron
member.summary: cyclotron: A device that uses an oscillating electric field and magnetic field to accelerate charged particles.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_TOF_MS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: TOF-MS: An instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed kinetic energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_time_of_flight_mass_spectrometer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: time-of-flight mass spectrometer: An instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed kinetic energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_TLF
member.summary: TLF: Energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer that is accomplished by introducing a time delay between the formation of the ions and the application of the accelerating voltage pulse.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_time_lag_focusing
member.summary: time lag focusing: Energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer that is accomplished by introducing a time delay between the formation of the ions and the application of the accelerating voltage pulse.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_TIC
member.summary: TIC: The sum of all the separate ion currents carried by the ions of different m/z contributing to a complete mass spectrum or in a specified m/z range of a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_total_ion_current
member.summary: total ion current: The sum of all the separate ion currents carried by the ions of different m/z contributing to a complete mass spectrum or in a specified m/z range of a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SWIFT
member.summary: SWIFT: A technique to create excitation waveforms for ions in FT-ICR mass spectrometer or Paul ion trap. An excitation waveform in the time-domain is generated by taking the inverse Fourier transform of an appropriate frequency-domain programmed excitation spectrum, in which the resonance frequencies of ions to be excited are included. This technique may be used for selection of precursor ions in MS2 experiments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_stored_waveform_inverse_fourier_transform
member.summary: stored waveform inverse fourier transform: A technique to create excitation waveforms for ions in FT-ICR mass spectrometer or Paul ion trap. An excitation waveform in the time-domain is generated by taking the inverse Fourier transform of an appropriate frequency-domain programmed excitation spectrum, in which the resonance frequencies of ions to be excited are included. This technique may be used for selection of precursor ions in MS2 experiments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SSMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: SSMS: Mass spectrometry using spark ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Spark_Source_Mass_Spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Spark Source Mass Spectrometry: Mass spectrometry using spark ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SORI
member.summary: SORI: A technique associated with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR) mass spectrometry to carry out ion/neutral reactions such as low-energy collision-induced dissociation. A radio-frequency electric field of slightly off-resonance to the cyclotron frequency of the reactant ion cyclically accelerates and decelerates the reactant ion that is confined in the Penning ion trap. The ion's orbit does not exceed the dimensions of ion trap while the ion undergoes an ion/neutral species process that produces a high average translational energy for an extended time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_sustained_off_resonance_irradiation
member.summary: sustained off-resonance irradiation: A technique associated with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR) mass spectrometry to carry out ion/neutral reactions such as low-energy collision-induced dissociation. A radio-frequency electric field of slightly off-resonance to the cyclotron frequency of the reactant ion cyclically accelerates and decelerates the reactant ion that is confined in the Penning ion trap. The ion's orbit does not exceed the dimensions of ion trap while the ion undergoes an ion/neutral species process that produces a high average translational energy for an extended time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SIFT
member.summary: SIFT: A device in which m/z selected ions are entrained in an inert carrier gas and undergo ion-molecule reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_selected_ion_flow_tube
member.summary: selected ion flow tube: A device in which m/z selected ions are entrained in an inert carrier gas and undergo ion-molecule reactions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SI_OBSOLETE
member.summary: SI: The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_suface_ionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: suface ionization: The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SEND
member.summary: SEND: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the matrix is covalently linked to the target surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_surface_enhanced_neat_desorption
member.summary: surface enhanced neat desorption: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the matrix is covalently linked to the target surface.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_SELDI
member.summary: SELDI: The formation of ionized species in the gas phase from analytes deposited on a particular surface substrate which is irradiated with a laser beam of which wavelength is absorbed by the surface. See also desorption/ionization on silicon and laser desorption/ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_surface_enhanced_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: surface enhanced laser desorption ionization: The formation of ionized species in the gas phase from analytes deposited on a particular surface substrate which is irradiated with a laser beam of which wavelength is absorbed by the surface. See also desorption/ionization on silicon and laser desorption/ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_RGA_OBSOLETE
member.summary: RGA: A mass spectrometer used to measure the composition and pressure of gasses in an evacuated chamber.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_residual_gas_analyzer_OBSOLETE
member.summary: residual gas analyzer: A mass spectrometer used to measure the composition and pressure of gasses in an evacuated chamber.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_REMPI
member.summary: REMPI: Multiphoton ionization in which the ionization cross section is significantly enhanced because the energy of the incident photons is resonant with an intermediate excited state of the neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_resonance_enhanced_multiphoton_ionization
member.summary: resonance enhanced multiphoton ionization: Multiphoton ionization in which the ionization cross section is significantly enhanced because the energy of the incident photons is resonant with an intermediate excited state of the neutral species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_q
member.summary: q: A transmission quadrupole to which an oscillating potential is applied so as to focus a beam of ions through a collision gas with no m/z separation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_collision_quadrupole
member.summary: collision quadrupole: A transmission quadrupole to which an oscillating potential is applied so as to focus a beam of ions through a collision gas with no m/z separation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_PyMS
member.summary: PyMS: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is heated to the point of decomposition and the gaseous decomposition products are introduced into the ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_pyrolysis_mass_spectrometry
member.summary: pyrolysis mass spectrometry: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is heated to the point of decomposition and the gaseous decomposition products are introduced into the ion source.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_PI
member.summary: PI: The ionization of an atom or molecule by a photon, written M + h? ? M^+ + e. The term photon impact is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_photoionization
member.summary: photoionization: The ionization of an atom or molecule by a photon, written M + h? ? M^+ + e. The term photon impact is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_NRMS
member.summary: NRMS: With this technique, m/z selected ions form neutrals by charge transfer to a collision gas or by dissociation. The neutrals are separated from the remaining ions and ionized in collisions with a second gas. This method is used to investigate reaction intermediates and other unstable species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_neutralization_reionization_mass_spectrometry
member.summary: neutralization reionization mass spectrometry: With this technique, m/z selected ions form neutrals by charge transfer to a collision gas or by dissociation. The neutrals are separated from the remaining ions and ionized in collisions with a second gas. This method is used to investigate reaction intermediates and other unstable species.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_NICI
member.summary: NICI: Chemical ionization that results in the formation of negative ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Negative_Ion_chemical_ionization
member.summary: Negative Ion chemical ionization: Chemical ionization that results in the formation of negative ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MSn_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MSn: Multiple stages of precursor ion m/z selection followed by product ion detection for successive progeny ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_multiple_stage_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: multiple stage mass spectrometry: Multiple stages of precursor ion m/z selection followed by product ion detection for successive progeny ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_MS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MS/MS: The acquisition, study and spectra of the electrically charged products or precursors of a m/z selected ion or ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometry_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry: The acquisition, study and spectra of the electrically charged products or precursors of a m/z selected ion or ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MS: The branch of science that deals with all aspects of mass spectrometers and the results obtained with these instruments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass spectrometry: The branch of science that deals with all aspects of mass spectrometers and the results obtained with these instruments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MIKES_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MIKES: Spectra that are obtained from a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector in reverse geometry. The accelerating voltage, V, and the magnetic sector field, B, are set at fixed values to select the precursor ions, which are then allowed to dissociate or to react in a field free region between the two sectors. The kinetic energy product ions of m/z selected precursor ions is analyzed by scanning the electric sector field, E. The width of the product ion spectrum peaks is related to the kinetic energy release distribution (KERD) for the dissociation process.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_analyzed_ion_kinetic_energy_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass analyzed ion kinetic energy spectrometry: Spectra that are obtained from a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector in reverse geometry. The accelerating voltage, V, and the magnetic sector field, B, are set at fixed values to select the precursor ions, which are then allowed to dissociate or to react in a field free region between the two sectors. The kinetic energy product ions of m/z selected precursor ions is analyzed by scanning the electric sector field, E. The width of the product ion spectrum peaks is related to the kinetic energy release distribution (KERD) for the dissociation process.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_LD_OBSOLETE
member.summary: LD: The formation of ions through the interaction of a laser with a material or with gas-phase ions or molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Laser_Ionization_MERGE_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Laser Ionization MERGE: The formation of ions through the interaction of a laser with a material or with gas-phase ions or molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Laser_Desorption_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Laser Desorption: The formation of ions through the interaction of a laser with a material or with gas-phase ions or molecules.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_KERD_OBSOLETE
member.summary: KERD: Distribution of values of translational kinetic energy release for an ensemble of metastable ions undergoing a specific dissociation reaction.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_kinetic_energy_release_distribution_OBSOLETE
member.summary: kinetic energy release distribution: Distribution of values of translational kinetic energy release for an ensemble of metastable ions undergoing a specific dissociation reaction.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IT
member.summary: IT: A device for spatially confining ions using electric and magnetic fields alone or in combination.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_trap
member.summary: ion trap: A device for spatially confining ions using electric and magnetic fields alone or in combination.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IRMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: IRMS: The measurement of the relative quantity of the different isotopes of an element in a material with a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_isotope_ratio_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: isotope ratio mass spectrometry: The measurement of the relative quantity of the different isotopes of an element in a material with a mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IRMPD
member.summary: IRMPD: Multiphoton ionization where the reactant ion dissociates as a result of the absorption of multiple infrared photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_infrared_multiphoton_dissociation
member.summary: infrared multiphoton dissociation: Multiphoton ionization where the reactant ion dissociates as a result of the absorption of multiple infrared photons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: IMS: The separation of ions according to their velocity through a buffer gas under the influence of an electric field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_mobility_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion mobility spectrometry: The separation of ions according to their velocity through a buffer gas under the influence of an electric field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IKES_OBSOLETE
member.summary: IKES: A method of analysis in which a beam of ions is separated according to the ratio of its translational energy to charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ion_kinetic_energy_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ion kinetic energy spectrometry: A method of analysis in which a beam of ions is separated according to the ratio of its translational energy to charge.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_GD_MS
member.summary: GD-MS: The formation of ions in the gas phase and from solid samples at the cathode by application of a voltage to a low pressure gas.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_glow_discharge_ionization
member.summary: glow discharge ionization: The formation of ions in the gas phase and from solid samples at the cathode by application of a voltage to a low pressure gas.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FI
member.summary: FI: The removal of electrons from any species by interaction with a high electric field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_field_ionization
member.summary: field ionization: The removal of electrons from any species by interaction with a high electric field.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FD
member.summary: FD: The formation of gas-phase ions from a material deposited on a solid surface in the presence of a high electric field. Because this process may encompass ionization by field ionization or other mechanisms, it is not recommended as a synonym for field desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_field_desorption
member.summary: field desorption: The formation of gas-phase ions from a material deposited on a solid surface in the presence of a high electric field. Because this process may encompass ionization by field ionization or other mechanisms, it is not recommended as a synonym for field desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FAIMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: FAIMS: The separation of ions between two concentric cylindrical electrodes due to application of a high voltage asymmetric waveform whereby ions migrate towards one of the two electrodes depending on the ratio of the high- to low-field mobility of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_high_field_asymmetric_waveform_ion_mobility_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: high-field asymmetric waveform ion mobility spectrometry: The separation of ions between two concentric cylindrical electrodes due to application of a high voltage asymmetric waveform whereby ions migrate towards one of the two electrodes depending on the ratio of the high- to low-field mobility of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FA
member.summary: FA: An ion source immersed in a flow of helium or other inert buffer gas that carries the ions through a meter-long reactor at pressures around 100 Pa.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_flowing_afterglow
member.summary: flowing afterglow: An ion source immersed in a flow of helium or other inert buffer gas that carries the ions through a meter-long reactor at pressures around 100 Pa.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ESA
member.summary: ESA: A device consisting of conducting parallel plates, concentric cylinders or concentric spheres that separates charged particles according to their kinetic energy by means of an electric field that is constant in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electrostatic_energy_analyzer
member.summary: electrostatic energy analyzer: A device consisting of conducting parallel plates, concentric cylinders or concentric spheres that separates charged particles according to their kinetic energy by means of an electric field that is constant in time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_EM
member.summary: EM: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons. The secondary electrons are then accelerated to other electrodes or parts of a continuous electrode to produce further secondary electrons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_multiplier
member.summary: electron multiplier: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons. The secondary electrons are then accelerated to other electrodes or parts of a continuous electrode to produce further secondary electrons.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_EIEIO_OBSOLETE
member.summary: EIEIO: The reaction of an ion with an electron in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_induced_excitation_in_organics_OBSOLETE
member.summary: electron-induced excitation in organics: The reaction of an ion with an electron in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_EE_OBSOLETE
member.summary: EE: An ion containing no unpaired electrons in its ground electronic state, e.g. CH3+ in its ground state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_even_electron_ion_OBSOLETE
member.summary: even-electron ion: An ion containing no unpaired electrons in its ground electronic state, e.g. CH3+ in its ground state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ECD
member.summary: ECD: A process in which a multiply protonated molecules interacts with a low energy electrons. Capture of the electron leads the liberation of energy and a reduction in charge state of the ion with the production of the (M + nH) (n-1)+ odd electron ion, which readily fragments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_capture_dissociation
member.summary: electron capture dissociation: A process in which a multiply protonated molecules interacts with a low energy electrons. Capture of the electron leads the liberation of energy and a reduction in charge state of the ion with the production of the (M + nH) (n-1)+ odd electron ion, which readily fragments.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_DLI
member.summary: DLI: The delivery of a liquid sample into a mass spectrometer for spray or desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_direct_liquid_introduction
member.summary: direct liquid introduction: The delivery of a liquid sample into a mass spectrometer for spray or desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_DIP
member.summary: DIP: A device for introducing a solid or liquid sample into a mass spectrometer ion source for desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_direct_insertion_probe
member.summary: direct insertion probe: A device for introducing a solid or liquid sample into a mass spectrometer ion source for desorption ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_DI
member.summary: DI: The formation of ions from a solid or liquid material after the rapid vaporization of that sample.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_desorption_ionization
member.summary: desorption ionization: The formation of ions from a solid or liquid material after the rapid vaporization of that sample.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_DE
member.summary: DE: The application of the accelerating voltage pulse after a time delay in desorption ionization from a surface. The extraction delay can produce energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_delayed_extraction
member.summary: delayed extraction: The application of the accelerating voltage pulse after a time delay in desorption ionization from a surface. The extraction delay can produce energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_CS
member.summary: CS: The reaction of a positive ion with an atom or molecule that results in the removal of one or more electrons from the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_stripping
member.summary: charge stripping: The reaction of a positive ion with an atom or molecule that results in the removal of one or more electrons from the ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_CRM_OBSOLETE
member.summary: CRM: MSn experiment with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_consecutive_reaction_monitoring_OBSOLETE_1000244
member.summary: consecutive reaction monitoring: MSn experiment with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_CRF_OBSOLETE
member.summary: CRF: A fragmentation of an even-electron ion in which the cleaved bond is not adjacent to the apparent charge site.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_charge_remote_fragmentation_OBSOLETE
member.summary: charge-remote fragmentation: A fragmentation of an even-electron ion in which the cleaved bond is not adjacent to the apparent charge site.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_BIRD
member.summary: BIRD: A special case of infrared multiphoton dissociation wherein excitation of the reactant ion is caused by absorption of infrared photons radiating from heated blackbody surroundings, which are usually the walls of a vacuum chamber. See also infrared multiphoton dissociation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_blackbody_infrared_radiative_dissociation
member.summary: blackbody infrared radiative dissociation: A special case of infrared multiphoton dissociation wherein excitation of the reactant ion is caused by absorption of infrared photons radiating from heated blackbody surroundings, which are usually the walls of a vacuum chamber. See also infrared multiphoton dissociation.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_APPI_OBSOLETE
member.summary: APPI: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Atmostpheric_Pressure_Photoionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Atmostpheric Pressure Photoionization: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_API
member.summary: API: Any ionization process in which ions are formed in the gas phase at atmospheric pressure.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_ionization
member.summary: atmospheric pressure ionization: Any ionization process in which ions are formed in the gas phase at atmospheric pressure.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_AP_MALDI
member.summary: AP MALDI: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the sample target is at atmospheric pressure and the ions formed by the pulsed laser are sampled through a small aperture into the mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_matrix_assisted_laser_desorption_ionization
member.summary: atmospheric pressure matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the sample target is at atmospheric pressure and the ions formed by the pulsed laser are sampled through a small aperture into the mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_AMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: AMS: A mass spectrometry technique in which atoms extracted from a sample are ionized, accelerated to MeV energies and separated according to their momentum, charge and energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_accelerator_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: accelerator mass spectrometry: A mass spectrometry technique in which atoms extracted from a sample are ionized, accelerated to MeV energies and separated according to their momentum, charge and energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_u_OBSOLETE
member.summary: u: A non-SI unit of mass (u) defined as one twelfth of ^12 C in its ground state and equal to 1.660 538 86(28) x 10^-27 kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_unified_atomic_mass_unit_OBSOLETE
member.summary: unified atomic mass unit: A non-SI unit of mass (u) defined as one twelfth of ^12 C in its ground state and equal to 1.660 538 86(28) x 10^-27 kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_transmission
member.summary: transmission: The ratio of the number of ions leaving a region of a mass spectrometer to the number entering that region.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_TIC_chromatogram
member.summary: TIC chromatogram: Representation of the total ion current detected in each of a series of mass spectra versus time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_total_ion_current_chromatogram
member.summary: total ion current chromatogram: Representation of the total ion current detected in each of a series of mass spectra versus time.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_resolving_power_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass resolving power: In a mass spectrum, the observed mass divided by the difference between two masses that can be separated. The method by which delta m was obtained and the mass at which the measurement was made should be reported.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_PA_OBSOLETE
member.summary: PA: The proton affinity of a species M is defined as the negative of the enthalpy change for the reaction M + H+ ->[M+H]+, where all species are in their ground rotational, vibrational and electronic states.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_proton_affinity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: proton affinity: The proton affinity of a species M is defined as the negative of the enthalpy change for the reaction M + H+ ->[M+H]+, where all species are in their ground rotational, vibrational and electronic states.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_peak_intensity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: peak intensity: The height or area of a peak in a mass spectrum.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_peak
member.summary: peak: A localized region of relatively large ion signal in a mass spectrum. Although peaks are often associated with particular ions, the terms peak and ion should not be used interchangeably.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_odd_electron_rule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: odd-electron rule: Odd-electron ions may dissociate to form either odd or even-electron ions, whereas even-electron ions generally form even-electron fragment ions.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nominal_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nominal mass: The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the mass of the most abundant isotope of each element rounded to the nearest integer value.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_nitrogen_rule_OBSOLETE
member.summary: nitrogen rule: An organic molecule containing the elements C, H, O, S, P, or halogen has an odd nominal mass if it contains an odd number of nitrogen atoms.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MPI
member.summary: MPI: Photoionization of an atom or molecule in which in two or more photons are absorbed.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_multiphoton_ionization
member.summary: multiphoton ionization: Photoionization of an atom or molecule in which in two or more photons are absorbed.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_MBMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: MBMS: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is introduced into the mass spectrometer as a molecular beam.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_molecular_beam_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: molecular beam mass spectrometry: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is introduced into the mass spectrometer as a molecular beam.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_monoisotopic_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: monoisotopic mass: The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the mass of the most abundant isotope of each element.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_molecular_mass
member.summary: molecular mass: Mass of a molecule measured in unified atomic mass units (u or Da).

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_number_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass number: The sum of the protons and neutrons in an atom, molecule or ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_mass_defect_OBSOLETE
member.summary: mass defect: The difference between the monoisotopic and nominal mass of a molecule or atom.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_magnetic_deflection
member.summary: magnetic deflection: The deflection of charged particles in a magnetic field due to a force equal to qvxB where q is the particle charge, v its velocity and B the magnetic field. Magnetic deflection of an ion beam is used for m/z separation in a magnetic sector mass spectrometer.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IDMS_OBSOLETE
member.summary: IDMS: A quantitative mass spectrometry technique in which an isotopically enriched compound is used as an internal standard.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_isotope_dilution_mass_spectrometry_OBSOLETE
member.summary: isotope dilution mass spectrometry: A quantitative mass spectrometry technique in which an isotopically enriched compound is used as an internal standard.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_IE_OBSOLETE
member.summary: IE: The minimum energy required to remove an electron from an atom or molecule to produce a positive ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ionization_energy_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ionization energy: The minimum energy required to remove an electron from an atom or molecule to produce a positive ion.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ionization_efficiency_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ionization efficiency: The ratio of the number of ions formed to the number of electrons, molecules or photons used.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ionization_cross_section_OBSOLETE
member.summary: ionization cross section: A measure of the probability that a given ionization process will occur when an atom or molecule interacts with a photon, electron, atom or molecule.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FFR
member.summary: FFR: A section of a mass spectrometer in which there are no electric or magnetic fields.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_field_free_region
member.summary: field-free region: A section of a mass spectrometer in which there are no electric or magnetic fields.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_exact_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: exact mass: The calculated mass of an ion or molecule containing a single isotope of each atom.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_energy_obsolete_OBSOLETE
member.summary: electron energy obsolete: The potential difference through which electrons are accelerated before they are used to bring about electron ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_EA_OBSOLETE
member.summary: EA: The electron affinity of M is the minimum energy required for the process M- ? M + e where M- and M are in their ground rotational, vibrational and electronic states and the electron has zero kinetic energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electron_affinity_OBSOLETE
member.summary: electron affinity: The electron affinity of M is the minimum energy required for the process M- ? M + e where M- and M are in their ground rotational, vibrational and electronic states and the electron has zero kinetic energy.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_dalton_OBSOLETE
member.summary: dalton: A non-SI unit of mass (symbol Da) that is equal to the unified atomic mass unit: 1.660 538 86(28) x 10^-27 kg.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_OBSOLETE_charge_number_OBSOLETE
member.summary: OBSOLETE charge number: The total charge on an ion divided by the electron charge e. OBSOLETED 2009-10-27 since this was viewed as a duplication of 00041 charge state.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_BP
member.summary: BP: The peak in a mass spectrum that has the greatest intensity. This term may be applied to the spectra of pure substances or mixtures.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_base_peak
member.summary: base peak: The peak in a mass spectrum that has the greatest intensity. This term may be applied to the spectra of pure substances or mixtures.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_AE_OBSOLETE
member.summary: AE: The minimum energy that must be imparted to an atom or molecule to produce a specified ion. The term appearance potential is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_appearance_energy_OBSOLETE
member.summary: appearance energy: The minimum energy that must be imparted to an atom or molecule to produce a specified ion. The term appearance potential is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_average_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: average mass: The mass of an ion or molecule calculated using the average mass of each element weighted for its natural isotopic abundance.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_accurate_mass_OBSOLETE
member.summary: accurate mass: An experimentally determined mass that is can be to determine a unique elemental formula. For ions less than 200 u, a measurement with 5 ppm accuracy is sufficient to determine the elemental composition.

member.summary: SRM: Data acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z selected precursor ions recorded via multiple stages of mass spectrometry. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed in time or in space.

member.summary: selected reaction monitoring: Data acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z selected precursor ions recorded via multiple stages of mass spectrometry. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed in time or in space.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_post_source_decay
member.summary: post-source decay: A technique specific to reflectron time-of-flight mass spectrometers where product ions of metastable transitions or collision-induced dissociations generated in the drift tube prior to entering the reflectron are m/z separated to yield product ion spectra.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_PD
member.summary: PD: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_plasma_desorption
member.summary: plasma desorption: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_collisionally_activated_dissociation
member.summary: collisionally activated dissociation: The dissociation of an ion after collisional excitation. The term collisional-activated dissociation is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Channeltron_Detector
member.summary: Channeltron Detector: A horn-shaped (or cone-shaped) continuous dynode particle multiplier. The ion strikes the inner surface of the device and induces the production of secondary electrons that in turn impinge on the inner surfaces to produce more secondary electrons. This avalanche effect produces an increase in signal in the final measured current pulse.

member.summary: quadrupole ion trap: Quadrupole Ion Trap mass analyzer captures the ions in a three dimensional ion trap and then selectively ejects them by varying the RF and DC potentials.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_quadrupole
member.summary: quadrupole: A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_magnetic_sector
member.summary: magnetic sector: A device that produces a magnetic field perpendicular to a charged particle beam that deflects the beam to an extent that is proportional to the particle momentum per unit charge. For a monoenergetic beam, the deflection is proportional to m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FT_ICR
member.summary: FT_ICR: A mass spectrometer based on the principle of ion cyclotron resonance in which an ion in a magnetic field moves in a circular orbit at a frequency characteristic of its m/z value. Ions are coherently excited to a larger radius orbit using a pulse of radio frequency energy and their image charge is detected on receiver plates as a time domain signal. Fourier transformation of the time domain signal results in a frequency domain signal which is converted to a mass spectrum based in the inverse relationship between frequency and m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fourier_transform_ion_cyclotron_resonance_mass_spectrometer
member.summary: fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometer: A mass spectrometer based on the principle of ion cyclotron resonance in which an ion in a magnetic field moves in a circular orbit at a frequency characteristic of its m/z value. Ions are coherently excited to a larger radius orbit using a pulse of radio frequency energy and their image charge is detected on receiver plates as a time domain signal. Fourier transformation of the time domain signal results in a frequency domain signal which is converted to a mass spectrum based in the inverse relationship between frequency and m/z.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_FAB
member.summary: FAB: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of neutral atoms having a translational energy of several thousand eV with a sample that is typically dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also secondary ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_fast_atom_bombardment_ionization
member.summary: fast atom bombardment ionization: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of neutral atoms having a translational energy of several thousand eV with a sample that is typically dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also secondary ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_ESI
member.summary: ESI: A process in which ionized species in the gas phase are produced from an analyte-containing solution via highly charged fine droplets, by means of spraying the solution from a narrow-bore needle tip at atmospheric pressure in the presence of a high electric field. When a pressurized gas is used to aid in the formation of a stable spray, the term pneumatically assisted electrospray ionization is used. The term ion spray is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_electrospray_ionization
member.summary: electrospray ionization: A process in which ionized species in the gas phase are produced from an analyte-containing solution via highly charged fine droplets, by means of spraying the solution from a narrow-bore needle tip at atmospheric pressure in the presence of a high electric field. When a pressurized gas is used to aid in the formation of a stable spray, the term pneumatically assisted electrospray ionization is used. The term ion spray is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_EI_OBSOLETE
member.summary: EI: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_Electronic_Ionization_OBSOLETE
member.summary: Electronic Ionization: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_CI
member.summary: CI: The formation of a new ion by the reaction of a neutral species with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton or other charged species between the reactants. When a positive ion results from chemical ionization the term may be used without qualification. When a negative ion results the term negative ion chemical ionization should be used. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemi-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_chemical_ionization
member.summary: chemical ionization: The formation of a new ion by the reaction of a neutral species with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton or other charged species between the reactants. When a positive ion results from chemical ionization the term may be used without qualification. When a negative ion results the term negative ion chemical ionization should be used. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemi-ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_APCI
member.summary: APCI: Chemical ionization that takes place at atmospheric pressure as opposed to the reduced pressure is normally used for chemical ionization.

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_atmospheric_pressure_chemical_ionization

member.name: F:pwiz.CLI.cv.CVID.MS_thomson
member.summary: thomson: Three-character symbol m/z is used to denote the quantity formed by dividing the mass of an ion in unified atomic mass units by its charge number (regardless of sign). The symbol is written in italicized lower case letters with no spaces. Note 1: The term mass-to-charge-ratio is deprecated. Mass-to-charge ratio has been used for the abscissa of a mass spectrum, although the quantity measured is not the quotient of the ion's mass to its electric charge. The three-character symbol m/z is recommended for the quantity that is the independent variable in a mass spectrum Note 2: The proposed unit thomson (Th) is deprecated.
